# Day 5 - Apex Introduction

## 1. What is Apex?

Apex is Salesforce’s programming language used to add custom business logic to applications. It is similar to Java and runs on the Salesforce platform.

Developers use Apex when business requirements cannot be completed using only clicks or configuration tools like Flow Builder.

Apex helps to:
- Automate complex processes
- Perform calculations
- Validate data
- Integrate external systems
- Create custom APIs and services

Apex runs securely on Salesforce servers and supports object-oriented programming concepts.

---

# 2. Difference

## Flow vs Apex

| Flow | Apex |
|------|------|
| No-code automation tool | Programming language |
| Uses drag-and-drop interface | Uses code |
| Easy for admins | Used by developers |
| Best for simple automation | Best for complex logic |
| Faster development | More flexible and powerful |
| Limited customization | Advanced customization possible |

---

## Configuration vs Coding

| Configuration | Coding |
|--------------|--------|
| Click-based setup | Written using code |
| Easy to maintain | Requires programming knowledge |
| Faster for simple tasks | Better for advanced requirements |
| Uses tools like Flow and Validation Rules | Uses Apex and Visualforce/LWC |
| Limited flexibility | Highly customizable |

---

# 3. Real Examples Where Apex Is Needed

## 1. Automatic Scholarship Eligibility Calculation

When a student record is updated:
- Calculate percentage
- Check attendance
- Verify income criteria
- Automatically decide scholarship eligibility

This logic may become too complex for Flow alone.

---

## 2. Integration with External Payment Gateway

Apex is used to:
- Connect with external APIs
- Verify payment status
- Update fee records automatically

Flows cannot handle advanced API integrations efficiently.

---

## 3. Bulk Student Data Processing

If thousands of student records need:
- Ranking
- Result generation
- Attendance calculations

Apex batch processing is used for better performance.

